<DocsShell
  title="Security and trust"
  description="Trust boundaries for secrets, generated files, hosted auth, sessions, and sparse storage in the Devbox alpha."
>
  <h2>Secrets</h2>
  <p>
    Devbox should block unsafe secret capture before object writes. Treat
    credentials, tokens, private keys, local database URLs, and service tokens
    as local environment data unless a reviewed policy says otherwise.
  </p>

  <h2>Generated files and overlays</h2>
  <p>
    Dependencies, caches, build output, editor state, and machine-specific
    configuration can be useful, but they are not always source. Devbox should
    make overlay state explicit so restoring a folder does not silently import
    unsafe local clutter.
  </p>

  <h2>Auth and session boundary</h2>
  <p>
    Browser code should not send WorkOS access tokens directly to the hosted
    Devbox API. The dashboard server verifies the WorkOS session, performs a
    server-to-server exchange, and uses the returned Devbox session token and
    device id for dashboard reads.
  </p>

  <h2>Sparse storage caveats</h2>
  <p>
    Chunk vocabulary and cache metadata do not mean sparse clone is complete.
    Remote protocol v2, chunk transfer, compression, lazy materialization, and
    OS virtual filesystem work remain later steps.
  </p>

  <div class="callout">
    <h3>Operational rule</h3>
    <p>
      Devbox should never pretend bytes are local when cache metadata says they
      are remote-only or partial. Hydration state is part of the trust boundary.
    </p>
  </div>

  <h2>Agent work</h2>
  <p>
    Agents should work in sandboxes or explicit workspaces and merge through
    reviewed boundaries. Generated patches, dependency changes, and local tool
    output should stay visible to the human who owns the folder.
  </p>
</DocsShell>
